   ├─ Turbulence profile from 35km to ground
   ├─ Aerosol scattering at quantum wavelengths
   ├─ Background photon statistics
   └─ Day/night transition effects

2. Quantum link performance
   ├─ Entanglement distribution rate vs altitude
   ├─ Fidelity vs atmospheric conditions
   ├─ Memory-assisted protocols
   └─ Comparison with theoretical models

3. Technology validation
   ├─ Component performance in near-space
   ├─ Thermal management at -60°C ambient
   ├─ Power system reliability
   └─ Data handling and storage

Launch Campaign:
├─ Location: Wanaka, New Zealand
├─ Launch window: December 2027 (summer)
├─ Flight path: Circumnavigate Southern Hemisphere
├─ Ground stations: NZ, Chile, South Africa
└─ Recovery: Off coast of Chile
```

PHASE 2: PATHFINDER SATELLITE (2030-2032)

2.1 Satellite Design and Fabrication

Satellite Name: "Quantum Starlight-1" (QS-1)

Bus Provider: SpaceX (based on Starlink bus with modifications)

```
Bus Specifications:
├─ Mass: 500kg (250kg payload + 250kg bus)
├─ Power: 800W peak (solar arrays: 6m² GaAs)
├─ Propulsion: Hall-effect thruster (80mN)
├─ Attitude control: 0.01° accuracy (star tracker + reaction wheels)
├─ Communication: S-band (TT&C), X-band (data), optical crosslink
├─ Design life: 3 years (goal: 5)
└─ Orbit: 600km Sun-synchronous, 10:30 LTDN

Payload Integration:
Location: SpaceX integration facility, Hawthorne CA
Schedule:
├─ Month 1-3: Bus modification for quantum payload
├─ Month 4-6: Payload delivery and integration
├─ Month 7-9: Environmental testing
├─ Month 10-12: Launch preparation
└─ Month 13: Launch
```

Quantum Payload Detailed Design:

```
Module 1: Entangled Photon Source (EPS)
├─ Dimensions: 400×300×200mm
├─ Mass: 15kg
├─ Power: 50W (peak), 30W (average)
├─ Thermal: 20°C ± 0.1°C (Peltier controlled)
├─ Redundancy: 2 identical sources, only one active
└─ Interfaces:
   ├─ Optical: 2× PM fiber outputs (1550nm)
   ├─ Electrical: 28V power, RS-422 control
   └─ Thermal: Heat pipe to radiator

Module 2: Quantum Memory (QMEM)
├─ Type: Rubidium vapor cell with buffer gas
├─ Dimensions: 300×200×150mm
├─ Mass: 8kg
├─ Power: 40W (mostly for heating)
├─ Temperature: 65°C ± 0.05°C
├─ Magnetic shielding: 3-layer Mu-metal
└─ Performance:
   ├─ Storage time: 1ms (goal: 10ms)
   ├─ Efficiency: >30%
   └─ Bandwidth: 10MHz

Module 3: Fine Pointing System (FPS)
├─ Telescope: 150mm diameter, off-axis Gregorian
├─ Fine steering mirror: 2-axis, 1kHz bandwidth
├─ Beacon detector: CMOS array (1024×1024)
├─ Tracking bandwidth: 500Hz closed loop
├─ Pointing accuracy: 0.5μrad RMS
└─ Vibration isolation: 40dB attenuation above 10Hz

Module 4: Classical Communication (COMC)
├─ Beacon laser: 976nm, 500mW for acquisition
├─ Data uplink: 1550nm, 10Mbps (QKD protocol)
├─ Data downlink: 1550nm, 100Mbps (quantum data)
├─ Crosslink: 1550nm, 1Gbps to other satellites
└─ Redundancy: Dual transmitters and receivers

Module 5: Data Processing Unit (DPU)
├─ Processor: Radiation-hardened LEON4 (quad-core)
├─ Memory: 256GB SSD with EDAC
├─ FPGA: Xilinx Kintex UltraScale (radiation tolerant)
├─ Interfaces: SpaceWire, MIL-STD-1553, Ethernet
└─ Software: Real-time Linux with quantum extensions

Module 6: Thermal Control System (TCS)
├─ Cryocooler: Stirling type, 1W at 2.8K
├─ Heat pipes: 6× ammonia pipes to radiators
├─ Radiators: 2m² deployable (200W heat rejection)
├─ Heaters: 100W distributed for survival
└─ Sensors: 50× temperature points monitored

Module 7: Power Conditioning (PCDU)
├─ Input: 28V unregulated from solar arrays
├─ Outputs: ±12V, ±5V, 3.3V, 2.8V (for detectors)
├─ Efficiency: >85% at all loads
├─ Protection: Overvoltage, overcurrent, latchup
└─ Battery: 100Ah Li-ion for eclipse operation
```

