PHASE 3: PILOT CONSTELLATION (2033-2035)

3.1 Constellation Design Optimization

Based on QS-1 results, optimize for 12-satellite network

```
Orbital Parameters (optimized):
├─ Altitude: 630km (slightly higher for longer contact)
├─ Inclination: 97.8° (Sun-synchronous)
├─ Planes: 4 planes with 3 satellites each
├─ Phase: 120° between satellites in same plane
├─ RAAN spacing: 90° between planes
└─ Local time: 10:30 descending node

Coverage Analysis:
├─ Single satellite: 15° elevation, 2800km diameter circle
├─ Three satellites: Continuous coverage over mid-latitudes
├─ Twelve satellites: 99% coverage between 50°N and 50°S
└─ Ground station visibility: >5 passes/day per station

Satellite Design (QS-2 series):
Improvements over QS-1:
├─ Mass reduction: 350kg (150kg payload + 200kg bus)
├─ Power increase: 1kW peak (larger solar arrays)
├─ Pointing improvement: 0.3μrad (better star tracker)
├─ Quantum memory: 10ms storage time
├─ Crosslinks: 4 optical terminals (adjacent satellites)
├─ Production: Batch of 12+2 spares
└─ Cost target: $25M per satellite at quantity 12

Ground Segment Expansion:
New ground stations:
├─ Beijing, China (40.0°N, 116.4°E)
├─ Bangalore, India (13.0°N, 77.6°E)
├─ Pretoria, South Africa (25.7°S, 28.2°E)
├─ Santiago, Chile (33.4°S, 70.7°W)
├─ Tokyo, Japan (35.7°N, 139.8°E)
└─ Upgrade existing 3 stations
```

